        "created_at": "2023-01-20T20:02:20.460Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Hello folks,</p>\n<p>I am trying to understand how disk snapshots work (technical details).</p>\n<p>When the <code>snapshot</code> command is issued and it runs the whitelisted binary, I get that file-system snapshot / copy is outside of the FDB logic and done by underlying filesystem / tool. However, what happens to transactions that are in progress. How does the restored instance know to discard uncommitted data. I don\u2019t see any read-version numbers passed to the snapshot binary. Senthil\u2019s <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hxjAS_1_qbE&amp;t=252s\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">talk</a> did mention that version-number is passed around, but can I assume this is internally handled by the sequence he is describing?</p>\n<p>In addition, is there a requirement that the snapshot binary finish within the typical 5-second txn time limit? Is the DB locked or write-transactions blocked during this process? His talk also started a workload in parallel, but he didn\u2019t mention if the write transactions waited/hung during the snapshot process.</p>\n<p>I appreciate any pointers.</p>\n<p>Thanks</p>\n<p>\u2013</p>\n<p>Hari</p>",
